<Base title="ostk docs — the OS for AI agents" description="How to install, configure, and use ostk — the local-first OS for AI agents.">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Documentation</h1>

    <h2>Quick start</h2>
    <pre><code># Install the binary
curl -fsSL https://ostk.ai/install | sh

# Initialize the OS on a repo
cd your-repo
ostk init

# Or use the interactive wizard
ostk init --guided

# (Optional) Download embeddings for semantic compression
ostk embeddings download

# Boot
ostk boot

# The OS is running. Agents use their normal tools.
# The kernel coordinates writes invisibly at the filesystem layer.</code></pre>

    <p><code>ostk init</code> downloads the governance bail from <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/ostk.ai">os-tack/ostk.ai</a>, verifies its GPG signature, and creates your project's <code>.ostk/</code> directory with HUMANFILE, Agentfile, pin.caps, and ostk.toml — personalized to your git identity.</p>

    <p>After boot, the OS:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Tracks every file write with generation counters</li>
      <li>Resolves conflicts between concurrent agents (Hot PR)</li>
      <li>Compresses shell output to save tokens</li>
      <li>Maintains an audit trail of every action</li>
    </ul>
    <p>No configuration needed. No <code>.ostk.yml</code>. The OS reads the repo and orients.</p>

    <h2>Architecture</h2>
    <img src="/diagrams/architecture-overview.svg" alt="ostk architecture: tools, squasher, kernel, and FCP drivers" class="diagram" />
    <p>ostk has two layers:</p>

    <h3>the kernel</h3>
    <p>A single Rust binary. Provides:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Process table and PTY supervision</li>
      <li>Filesystem with optimistic concurrency control (CAS writes, flock, gen_table)</li>
      <li>Hot PR conflict resolution (4 tiers: auto-merge, assisted, manual rebase, diagnostic)</li>
      <li>Generation table for file versioning with shadow storage for rollback</li>
      <li>Agent identity (monotonic counter) and heartbeat monitoring</li>
      <li>GPG web-of-trust identity — trust tiers T0–T3 with capability pins</li>
      <li>Privilege escalation (secrets, budget, tool access, model upgrades)</li>
      <li>Nudge queue — interrupt primitive for inter-agent/human-to-agent messaging</li>
      <li>Read elision (304 Not Modified) — redundant reads return ~5 tokens</li>
      <li>Output compression (VTE strip + dedup)
        <img src="/diagrams/compression-pipeline.svg" alt="Compression pipeline: raw output to compressed with 80% token savings" class="diagram diagram-wide" />
      </li>
      <li>MCP proxy (<code>ostk mcp</code>) — connect external MCP servers, expose tools via CLI</li>
      <li>Quota enforcement — per-agent token and cost budgets</li>
      <li>VerbCtx calling convention — ~45 verbs resolve as direct Rust function calls via <code>kernel::resolve::try_internal()</code>, shell fallback only when needed</li>
      <li>.language as unified tool surface — MCP tool schemas generated from .language entries, not hardcoded. One place, one format</li>
      <li>INIT execution engine — <code>.boot/INIT</code> is the authoritative boot sequence. Post-language verbs validated at boot</li>
      <li>Secret masking — structure-preserving masks at the <code>build_tool_result</code> chokepoint. Prefix + length visible, value hidden. Catches all leak vectors</li>
      <li>Model switch handoff — cross-provider <code>:model</code> builds a ~200 token lookup table (page table) with hot files, recent decisions, intent thread. <a href="/insights/model-switch-handoff">The new model boots with pointers, not data</a></li>
      <li>Session checkpoints — written at shutdown, read at boot. Retention keeps last 5. Session continuity across boundaries</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>fcp-* (device drivers)</h3>
    <p>Domain intelligence plugins. Each driver speaks a domain's native language:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>fcp-rust</strong>: Rust analyzer integration — diagnostics, type queries, refactoring</li>
      <li><strong>fcp-screen</strong>: Display and input — TUI rendering, keystroke capture</li>
      <li><strong>fcp-web</strong>: Web intelligence — page reading, link extraction</li>
      <li>More as needed. The kernel provides primitives. Drivers provide intelligence.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="tack-grammar">Tack grammar</h2>
    <p>Tack is the intent-capture language. You type shorthand. The OS compiles it.</p>
    <pre><code>:command object              # Basic command
:verb1 :verb2 :verb3         # Chain commands (sequential)
.p0 .p1 .p2                  # Priority shorthand
-&gt; flow                      # Sequence operator</code></pre>

    <p>Examples:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>You type</th><th>What happens</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>:compile</code></td><td>Unstructured thinking becomes executable needles</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>:compile :plan :ship</code></td><td>Compile, plan the work, commit</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>:needle add "fix auth" .p0</code></td><td>File a P0 needle</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>:calibrate</code></td><td>Retrospective on a thread</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Tack is not a fixed grammar. The OS learns your shorthand over sessions. What you type today becomes vocabulary tomorrow.</p>

